<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-09T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/3295</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Colombia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BP1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Belden</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-09T00:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 9, 1917, midnight</hi></date>.
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 10, 5
                                    p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Department’s telegram February 3, 1 p.m. Colombian Minister for
                                Foreign Affairs to-day acknowledged note without reference to
                                similar action. Commercial interests anxious. Some apprehension
                                exists as to invasion of Colombian territory by the United States to
                                protect canal if there is war. Germans here will agitate this issue.
                                    <pb facs="0402" n="230" xml:id="pg_230"/> I believe therefore
                                that the approval of Colombian treaty at this time would be
                                advantageous. See my telegram of February 3, 11 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d285fn1">Not printed; see <ref target="frus1917#pg_292">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, pp.
                                        292</ref>
                                    <hi rend="italic">et seq</hi>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>I have urged consuls to watch Germans.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_BP1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Belden</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>